<font color="#FF0000">THIS TRAIN DON'T STOP</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 12  6:25:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
The Vietnam Memorial stands in honor of those who died in Vietnam. Pure and simple. I also knew several who came home paralyzed or with loss of limb, or with grievous head wounds. I don't ever compare myself with them. It was tough for me - but not as tough as what they have to endure day after day.<br><br>
The Wall was not meant to &quot;shut us up&quot;. Some vets claim that it was built to soothe the guilt of those who rejected us. I say both the former and latter premises are cynical.<br><br>
More than once you have claimed in this dialogue that you have received no compensation for being &quot;right&quot;. In view of all that has transpired, and all that we have seen personally, and all that we have learned about the self centeredness of our socalled leaders, I agree that the war was wrong. However, my serving as a young man, - no matter what the cause - my answering the call to duty was the right decision for me.<br><br>
If you are looking for compensation: let it be that you have happened upon a group of veterans who are willing to let bygones be bygones. You can translate that however you wish.<br>
Many of us have undergone the struggle of trying to understand where YOU, and those others who refused service, are coming from. All this after toiling, &quot;carrying an 80 pound pack and cleaning an M16 in the dark&quot;. This is in keeping with putting the other person first.<br><br>
I was sent to Vietnam. When I returned, those loud voices who sent me, ignored me. I'm not talking about Macnamara and those others of whom you have referred. Ask other vets how they were received by the VFW! We were shunned by those who sent us and ridiculed by many who protested the war. Many, many, many more simply said nothing to us. What the hell! they had no sons or husbands, or brothers at risk! Why should they care about Vietnam?<br><br>
We are what our experiences have made us. Rather than continue in the 30 year role of being the poor relations in the American family, Vietnam veterans are coming to realize their importance as real leaders. This strength doesn't come from &quot;being right&quot;. It comes from *being*.<br><br>
Today the government receives the brunt of excoriation. People like Macnamara are still in the government. But, I shudder to think of what we would replace the present government with. Did the Democratic People's government give amnesty to those who opposed it?<br><br>
Your last paragraph reveals much. This is how I view things:<br>
Rather than being &quot;adrift&quot;, I feel that we are very much in control. Remember the medium of the Internet. The possibilities are endless. We are a long way from the end of the line.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


